1
00:00:30,072 --> 00:00:32,032
When I look back on it,

2
00:00:32,074 --> 00:00:35,285
I still can't make sense
of how a normal kid like me

3
00:00:35,327 --> 00:00:38,121
ever wound up meeting
Buck Howard.

4
00:00:38,164 --> 00:00:39,956
When I was five years old,

5
00:00:39,999 --> 00:00:41,374
my dad asked me what
I wanted to be

6
00:00:41,417 --> 00:00:43,585
when I grew up.

7
00:00:43,627 --> 00:00:46,963
I said I wanted to drive
a steamroller and he said, "No,

8
00:00:47,006 --> 00:00:48,590
you want to be a lawyer."

9
00:00:48,632 --> 00:00:51,217
I said astronaut.
He said lawyer.

10
00:00:51,260 --> 00:00:53,511
I said policeman.
He said lawyer.

11
00:00:53,554 --> 00:00:56,681
So we compromised... on lawyer,

12
00:00:56,724 --> 00:00:58,224
which is how, 20 years later,

13
00:00:58,267 --> 00:01:00,393
I ended up in law school.

14
00:01:00,436 --> 00:01:02,395
And even though
this was my father's dream,

15
00:01:02,438 --> 00:01:03,897
for the first couple of years

16
00:01:03,939 --> 00:01:05,440
I bought into the whole thing,

17
00:01:07,026 --> 00:01:08,818
until one day.

18
00:01:08,861 --> 00:01:12,155
I finished an exam early
and I just sat there thinking,

19
00:01:12,198 --> 00:01:15,950
thinking that somewhere
there must be somebody

20
00:01:15,993 --> 00:01:18,620
whose dream it is to be a lawyer,

21
00:01:18,662 --> 00:01:20,830
but after more than
two years in law school,

22
00:01:20,873 --> 00:01:23,166
I hadn't met a single one.

23
00:01:23,209 --> 00:01:26,461
And suddenly it occurred to me...

24
00:01:26,504 --> 00:01:28,046
I'm not happy.

25
00:01:28,089 --> 00:01:29,839
I gotta get out of here.

26
00:01:29,882 --> 00:01:31,508
So this moment right here

27
00:01:31,550 --> 00:01:33,551
became my last chance
to stop everything,

28
00:01:33,594 --> 00:01:35,386
hit pause,

29
00:01:35,429 --> 00:01:37,388
and find a dream
before it was too late.

30
00:01:37,431 --> 00:01:41,392
Late or not, it felt fantastic.

31
00:01:41,435 --> 00:01:44,479
Of course, I hadn't told
my father any of this,

32
00:01:44,522 --> 00:01:46,189
but I was pretty sure
that he'd understand.

33
00:01:46,232 --> 00:01:48,608
I just had to present my case.

34
00:01:48,651 --> 00:01:52,070
Hey, Dad. Well, school's tough.

35
00:01:52,113 --> 00:01:56,282
You know,
Contracts is really hard.

36
00:01:56,325 --> 00:01:59,702
See? I would have been
a terrible lawyer.

37
00:01:59,745 --> 00:02:01,371
The thrilling thing, though,

38
00:02:01,413 --> 00:02:04,040
is that now all I had were options.

39
00:02:04,083 --> 00:02:05,708
I could do anything I wanted.

40
00:02:05,751 --> 00:02:08,378
You name it,
I thought of being it.

41
00:02:08,420 --> 00:02:10,421
I could be a private investigator,

42
00:02:10,464 --> 00:02:12,507
a test driver for NASCAR,

43
00:02:12,550 --> 00:02:15,051
or a talk show host.

44
00:02:15,094 --> 00:02:17,345
How do you get
that job, anyway?

45
00:02:17,388 --> 00:02:20,098
The truth, though,
is that I did have an idea

46
00:02:20,141 --> 00:02:22,350
in the back of my head.

47
00:02:22,393 --> 00:02:25,728
I had always had this secret dream
of becoming a writer.

48
00:02:25,771 --> 00:02:28,398
And while I didn't know
how to get that job either,

49
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:31,109
I did have a pen and paper.

50
00:02:31,152 --> 00:02:33,528
So I just did what came naturally.

51
00:02:33,571 --> 00:02:35,613
And that's when I was hit
by something else...

52
00:02:35,656 --> 00:02:39,617
reality... the reality of having to
find something to do

53
00:02:39,660 --> 00:02:41,828
to pay for little things
like food and rent,

54
00:02:41,871 --> 00:02:44,747
and getting my car fixed.
I had to find a job,

55
00:02:44,790 --> 00:02:47,375
but who said it couldn't be
something with a little adventure,

56
00:02:47,418 --> 00:02:50,795
something with words like "celebrity"
and "performer" attached to it?

57
00:02:54,842 --> 00:02:56,342
And that's how it happened.

58
00:02:56,385 --> 00:02:58,845
That's how I found myself

59
00:02:58,888 --> 00:03:02,140
meeting the one and only
Great Buck Howard.

60
00:03:11,275 --> 00:03:12,775
You must be Troy.

61
00:03:12,818 --> 00:03:15,403
- I'm Gil.
- Oh, hi. I'm Troy.

62
00:03:15,446 --> 00:03:18,114
- Sorry I'm late.
- Relax. It's not a problem.

63
00:03:18,157 --> 00:03:19,741
Let's grab a seat.

64
00:03:21,243 --> 00:03:22,952
He should be here any minute.

65
00:03:22,995 --> 00:03:24,913
We were impressed
you'd been to law school.

66
00:03:24,955 --> 00:03:28,124
I should probably explain that. Uh...

67
00:03:28,167 --> 00:03:30,126
I didn't finish, actually.

68
00:03:30,169 --> 00:03:31,586
Good evening, Mr. Howard.

69
00:03:31,629 --> 00:03:32,962
Oh, here he is.

70
00:03:39,011 --> 00:03:41,054
Buck!

71
00:03:41,096 --> 00:03:43,181
Big Buck!

72
00:04:08,874 --> 00:04:10,375
I'm Buck Howard.

73
00:04:12,503 --> 00:04:14,504
Troy Gable.

74
00:04:14,546 --> 00:04:18,383
Young man, I am delighted
that you are interested in this job.

75
00:04:18,425 --> 00:04:21,010
I am very busy. I did over...

76
00:04:21,053 --> 00:04:22,845
One thought kept racing
through my mind as Buck talked...

77
00:04:22,888 --> 00:04:26,849
I had no idea who this guy was...

78
00:04:26,892 --> 00:04:28,851
and I guess it must have shown.

79
00:04:28,894 --> 00:04:31,396
You do know who I am, don't you?

80
00:04:31,438 --> 00:04:33,231
Uh...

81
00:04:33,274 --> 00:04:34,732
You have seen "The Tonight Show"?

82
00:04:34,775 --> 00:04:37,652
You have to say "with Johnny Carson,"

83
00:04:37,695 --> 00:04:40,238
not the nitwit who's on there now.

84
00:04:40,281 --> 00:04:42,031
Buck did "The Tonight Show"...
with Johnny...

85
00:04:42,074 --> 00:04:44,033
61 times.

86
00:04:44,076 --> 00:04:47,704
I think...
you're a magician, right?

87
00:04:47,746 --> 00:04:49,372
Buck's a mentalist.

88
00:04:49,415 --> 00:04:51,207
Magician is kind of
a dirty word around here.

89
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:53,751
I was a magician...
when I was three years old,

90
00:04:53,794 --> 00:04:57,463
but I evolved out of that. Not that
I have anything against magicians,

91
00:04:57,506 --> 00:04:59,424
as long as they're dead.

92
00:05:01,218 --> 00:05:02,885
Buck's been
on all the big shows...

93
00:05:02,928 --> 00:05:06,806
Jim Nabors, Jon Davidson,
Sally Jesse Raphael.

94
00:05:06,849 --> 00:05:09,225
Dinah... he was the co-host
on "Dinah!" many times.

95
00:05:09,268 --> 00:05:11,602
He's performed all over the world...
Las Vegas...

96
00:05:11,645 --> 00:05:13,646
but not lately.

97
00:05:15,691 --> 00:05:18,901
Yourjob would be
to take care of all of Buck's travel,

98
00:05:18,944 --> 00:05:20,570
and then to go
on the road with him

99
00:05:20,612 --> 00:05:23,239
to ensure the engagements
were handled smoothly.

100
00:05:23,282 --> 00:05:26,868
It is a very demanding
but ultimately rewarding job.

101
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:28,786
For instance,
in a few months' time

102
00:05:28,829 --> 00:05:31,247
we'd be very hard at work
on a benefit that I started

103
00:05:31,290 --> 00:05:33,875
for sick children
with my friend George Takei,

104
00:05:33,917 --> 00:05:37,253
who is perhaps best known
for his portrayal of Sulu

105
00:05:37,296 --> 00:05:40,256
on "Star Trek."
He is a dear friend.

106
00:05:40,299 --> 00:05:42,258
This certainly wasn't the kind ofjob

107
00:05:42,301 --> 00:05:44,010
my father would
have envisioned for me,

108
00:05:44,053 --> 00:05:46,888
but there was something
kind of exciting about Buck.

109
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:50,433
He told these long stories about
a world full of his famous friends...

110
00:05:50,476 --> 00:05:52,769
Johnny Carson, Ed McMahon...

111
00:05:52,811 --> 00:05:54,687
The Captain & Tennille.

112
00:05:56,106 --> 00:05:58,274
It was wonderful
to meet you, young man.

113
00:05:58,317 --> 00:06:00,276
I think this can all work out.

114
00:06:00,319 --> 00:06:02,070
Gil, call me later.

115
00:06:02,112 --> 00:06:04,072
So the job's yours if you want it...

116
00:06:04,114 --> 00:06:05,448
pays $650 a week to start.

117
00:06:05,491 --> 00:06:07,450
Uh...

118
00:06:10,954 --> 00:06:13,122
yeah, it sounds great.

119
00:06:13,165 --> 00:06:14,749
Good. You'll be going to
Bakersfield this weekend,

120
00:06:14,792 --> 00:06:16,376
somebody will meet you
and show you the ropes.

121
00:06:16,418 --> 00:06:17,418
Good luck, Troy.

122
00:06:17,461 --> 00:06:19,253
Thank you, Gil.

123
00:06:21,673 --> 00:06:24,300
Edward, your younger readers
may not be aware

124
00:06:24,343 --> 00:06:28,304
that it was actually Johnny Carson
who dubbed me the Great Buck Howard.

125
00:06:28,347 --> 00:06:30,807
Do you recall what trick
you did that night?

126
00:06:30,849 --> 00:06:32,850
It's not a trick. It's an effect.

127
00:06:32,893 --> 00:06:36,646
Okay, I'm sorry. I didn't realize
there was a difference.

128
00:06:36,688 --> 00:06:39,190
Troy.

129
00:06:39,233 --> 00:06:41,651
Edward, I'm going
to give you a coin.

130
00:06:41,693 --> 00:06:45,363
I would like you to grasp it
between your thumb and your forefinger.

131
00:06:45,406 --> 00:06:49,992
I'm going to count, and whenever
you feel compelled to do so,

132
00:06:50,035 --> 00:06:51,994
you simply drop the coin.
Do you understand?

133
00:06:52,037 --> 00:06:55,456
Ready? One, two,

134
00:06:55,499 --> 00:06:58,501
three.

135
00:06:58,544 --> 00:07:02,547
Troy, could you show Edward
what's written on that piece of paper?

136
00:07:08,679 --> 00:07:11,347
Welcome to Bakersfield!
I'm Sheila Heller.

137
00:07:11,390 --> 00:07:13,349
I'm Buck Howard.

138
00:07:14,893 --> 00:07:17,311
This is Alan, Troy...
and this is Edward.

139
00:07:17,354 --> 00:07:20,022
He is a magazine writer
who is doing a profile on me.

140
00:07:20,065 --> 00:07:21,691
- Oh, yeah.
- It's going to be a cover story, right?

141
00:07:21,733 --> 00:07:24,360
- Right.
- Buck needs to head back to the hotel

142
00:07:24,403 --> 00:07:25,862
to prepare for the performance,

143
00:07:25,904 --> 00:07:28,197
but if you could show
Troy and I around...

144
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:30,575
Oh, that would be no problem at all.

145
00:07:30,617 --> 00:07:32,577
I love to come to the venue first

146
00:07:32,619 --> 00:07:34,495
and meet the people like you

147
00:07:34,538 --> 00:07:37,957
who keep these places up
and running. Cha-cha-cha.

148
00:07:42,045 --> 00:07:45,631
Dude, check it out.
I like that... nice and big, bro.

149
00:07:50,095 --> 00:07:53,556
Right through here is where we have
the main celebrity dressing room,

150
00:07:53,599 --> 00:07:55,558
which of course is for Buck.

151
00:07:55,601 --> 00:07:58,561
- And we have snacks.
- Where's the brandy?

152
00:08:00,105 --> 00:08:02,023
Oh! God, I knew
we forgot something.

153
00:08:02,065 --> 00:08:03,691
I'm so sorry.

154
00:08:03,734 --> 00:08:05,234
- I'll send out for a bottle right away.
- Okay.

155
00:08:05,277 --> 00:08:06,986
Okay. Yeah. Sorry.

156
00:08:08,447 --> 00:08:09,822
- Excuse me.
- Go ahead.

157
00:08:09,865 --> 00:08:12,783
Okay. All right.

158
00:08:14,953 --> 00:08:16,579
Oh my God.

159
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:21,584
Ah, but it's part of my job.

160
00:08:21,627 --> 00:08:22,919
You know what I'm saying?

161
00:08:25,130 --> 00:08:27,131
There aren't many cues,
but don't let that lull you to sleep.

162
00:08:27,174 --> 00:08:28,508
Do you have that intro?

163
00:08:42,981 --> 00:08:45,900
Please tell Buck I am
so sorry about the crowd.

164
00:08:45,943 --> 00:08:47,818
I thought it would
at least be half full.

165
00:08:47,861 --> 00:08:50,613
Go tell Buck he's on,

166
00:08:50,656 --> 00:08:53,324
and if he asks,
tell him it's a huge crowd.

167
00:08:57,663 --> 00:08:59,121
So...

168
00:09:05,587 --> 00:09:06,963
Come in.

169
00:09:10,008 --> 00:09:11,801
- How's the crowd?
- Uh, it's pretty full.

170
00:09:11,843 --> 00:09:13,761
Pretty full?
What does that mean?

171
00:09:13,804 --> 00:09:16,597
Nothing. It's a big crowd.

172
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:19,141
- It's a packed house.
- Great! Let's do it.

173
00:09:20,352 --> 00:09:23,312
Uh, Buck, this way.

174
00:09:23,355 --> 00:09:25,898
Let's do it!

175
00:09:32,698 --> 00:09:34,156
Are you ready?

176
00:09:34,199 --> 00:09:35,950
Yes, of course
I'm ready. Let's go.

177
00:09:35,993 --> 00:09:38,286
He's ready. House lights down,
stage lights down, cue tape.

178
00:09:38,328 --> 00:09:41,330
...search in sullen silence
on a dull dark dock...

179
00:09:41,373 --> 00:09:45,626
Ladies and gentlemen, it is
my pleasure to introduce to you a man

180
00:09:45,669 --> 00:09:48,004
who has performed in over 27 countries

181
00:09:48,046 --> 00:09:50,631
on radio, television,
and other media,

182
00:09:50,674 --> 00:09:53,342
including "The Tonight Show
with Johnny Carson."

183
00:09:53,385 --> 00:09:55,678
- Presenting the Great Buck Howard!
- Spotlight.

184
00:10:01,852 --> 00:10:04,186
Whoa! There we go!

185
00:10:04,229 --> 00:10:07,023
Stupid amateurs.

186
00:10:07,065 --> 00:10:09,650
I love this town.

187
00:10:09,693 --> 00:10:13,571
All right. Next cue's in 15 minutes
when he goes over to the piano.

188
00:10:13,614 --> 00:10:16,407
I'll be outside.

189
00:10:16,450 --> 00:10:20,036
Now, ladies and gentlemen,
I will need a volunteer.

190
00:10:20,078 --> 00:10:22,038
In fact, these two handsome,

191
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:24,665
strapping young lads
down in front will do perfectly...

192
00:10:24,708 --> 00:10:28,044
Here's the thing
that struck me about Buck

193
00:10:28,086 --> 00:10:30,004
as I watched
the progression of his show:

194
00:10:30,047 --> 00:10:33,049
He was cheesy...
there was no denying that...

195
00:10:33,091 --> 00:10:36,093
but he also had
a sort of timeless charm

196
00:10:36,136 --> 00:10:38,095
that the audience
really seemed to love.

197
00:10:38,138 --> 00:10:40,306
Uh-oh.

198
00:10:40,349 --> 00:10:43,142
Uh-oh.

199
00:10:43,185 --> 00:10:48,064
Now, I asked you to choose
a number between one and 100.

200
00:10:48,106 --> 00:10:49,899
But you didn't, did you?

201
00:10:49,941 --> 00:10:53,027
I guess I didn't.

202
00:10:53,070 --> 00:10:57,782
Did you choose the number zero?

203
00:10:57,824 --> 00:10:59,700
Whoa.

204
00:10:59,743 --> 00:11:02,078
- Whoa, zero.
- God...

205
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:05,122
Zero.

206
00:11:06,792 --> 00:11:11,003
Isn't that wild, folks?
Isn't that wild?

207
00:11:11,046 --> 00:11:13,589
...deep and profound sleep.

208
00:11:13,632 --> 00:11:16,884
Nighty-night.

209
00:11:16,927 --> 00:11:20,763
What the world needs now

210
00:11:20,806 --> 00:11:24,767
Is love, sweet love...

211
00:11:24,810 --> 00:11:27,687
Now I'll need to impose
on you one last time

212
00:11:27,729 --> 00:11:29,313
before I vanish.

213
00:11:29,356 --> 00:11:32,358
I will need four volunteers,
two of whom

214
00:11:32,401 --> 00:11:34,402
will go with me
to the green room.

215
00:11:34,444 --> 00:11:37,488
The other two will stay
here in the auditorium...

216
00:11:37,531 --> 00:11:39,073
Hey.

217
00:11:39,116 --> 00:11:43,369
...and they will take
my entire fee in cash

218
00:11:43,412 --> 00:11:46,956
and they will hide
that fee in here.

219
00:11:46,998 --> 00:11:52,169
If I am unable to find
that cash when I return,

220
00:11:52,212 --> 00:11:56,424
that money will stay here
in Bakersfield, California.

221
00:11:56,466 --> 00:11:58,092
I love this town!

222
00:11:58,135 --> 00:12:01,887
I saw him do this
last week in Stockton.

223
00:12:01,930 --> 00:12:04,890
Apparently he's never
failed to find his money

224
00:12:04,933 --> 00:12:07,560
in over 5,000 tries.

225
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:09,186
Hmm.

226
00:12:09,229 --> 00:12:12,231
I'll let you choose
your four volunteers.

227
00:12:13,984 --> 00:12:17,069
Guys, come on.
We have to go to the green room.

228
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:25,035
Gentlemen, this is
my entire entourage,

229
00:12:25,078 --> 00:12:28,914
just so you can see there's
absolutely nothing fishy going on

230
00:12:28,957 --> 00:12:30,541
while they hide my money.

231
00:12:30,584 --> 00:12:32,334
You'll be my witnesses.

232
00:12:32,377 --> 00:12:35,337
Would either of you like
a signed photograph?

233
00:12:35,380 --> 00:12:36,922
- Oh...
- Yeah.

234
00:12:36,965 --> 00:12:41,010
Alan, some signed photos,
colored ones, please.

235
00:12:41,052 --> 00:12:43,220
I don't see
any of the colored ones.

236
00:12:43,263 --> 00:12:46,223
Seek and ye shall find, Alan.
They're in there.

237
00:12:46,266 --> 00:12:48,434
My ink pen, please. Ink pen.

238
00:12:50,896 --> 00:12:52,855
- Thank you, Troy.
- Black and white's fine.

239
00:12:52,898 --> 00:12:54,857
No, it's not. It's not fine.

240
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:57,568
- Alan?
- Buck, these are the only ones we have.

241
00:12:59,571 --> 00:13:02,031
Mr. Howard,
they're ready for you.

242
00:13:02,073 --> 00:13:04,074
Oh, well that's fantastic news.

243
00:13:04,117 --> 00:13:06,076
Sorry, folks,
there won't be any photograph

244
00:13:06,119 --> 00:13:07,870
due to Alan's incompetence.

245
00:13:07,913 --> 00:13:09,580
I'd still like a black and white.

246
00:13:09,623 --> 00:13:12,249
What's the point in having
a black and white?

247
00:13:12,292 --> 00:13:14,210
What's the point?

248
00:13:14,252 --> 00:13:15,753
Let's go.

249
00:13:19,216 --> 00:13:21,717
- Thanks a lot.
- I'm sorry.

250
00:13:56,711 --> 00:13:59,630
Sir, may I look
in your right shoe, please?

251
00:14:12,352 --> 00:14:16,021
Oh, well.
I thought it would be more.

252
00:14:18,316 --> 00:14:20,150
How did he do that?

253
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:22,319
I love this town!

254
00:14:26,241 --> 00:14:28,826
- ...in front of these people.
- The only humiliation is

255
00:14:28,869 --> 00:14:30,911
- that you're incompetent.
- That's not true!

256
00:14:30,954 --> 00:14:33,747
- It is true.
- Come out and say that to my face!

257
00:14:33,790 --> 00:14:35,749
Go on, get the hell out of here.

258
00:14:35,792 --> 00:14:37,751
Leave the petty cash with Troy.

259
00:14:37,794 --> 00:14:39,545
- That's my money.
- Oh yeah, Buck?

260
00:14:39,588 --> 00:14:41,255
Well, you suck!

261
00:14:43,717 --> 00:14:46,343
I can't train you anymore. You're gonna
have to figure it out for yourself.

262
00:14:46,386 --> 00:14:48,512
I don't even know where to begin.

263
00:14:48,555 --> 00:14:51,140
It's not that complicated. Listen,

264
00:14:51,182 --> 00:14:53,142
if you take this job,
you're an idiot.

265
00:14:53,184 --> 00:14:54,727
Do you underst...

266
00:14:54,769 --> 00:14:57,479
Troy, I'm sorry
you had to see this.

267
00:14:57,522 --> 00:15:00,524
Edward, this wouldn't be
a pleasant story.

268
00:15:00,567 --> 00:15:02,359
I'm sure you wouldn't
want to write that down.

269
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:04,361
Alan, I think it's time
for you to leave.

270
00:15:04,404 --> 00:15:06,989
- No, okay...
- Otherwise, I'm gonna call security.

271
00:15:07,032 --> 00:15:09,408
Oh, call security, you fossil!

272
00:15:16,958 --> 00:15:20,294
Well, I guess this
is adios, fellas.

273
00:15:25,926 --> 00:15:29,803
Excuse me for interrupting.
Could I have your autograph?

274
00:15:29,846 --> 00:15:33,223
Anything for a beautiful young lady.

275
00:15:33,266 --> 00:15:34,892
Oh!

276
00:15:37,228 --> 00:15:39,897
Did you enjoy the show?

277
00:15:39,940 --> 00:15:43,359
Oh, I didn't see the show. In fact,
I didn't even know you were here.

278
00:15:43,401 --> 00:15:45,903
There was nothing about it
in the paper or anything.

279
00:15:45,946 --> 00:15:50,282
I used to watch you all the time
on the Carson show, though.

280
00:15:50,325 --> 00:15:51,992
That's super.

281
00:15:52,035 --> 00:15:53,869
There you go.

282
00:15:53,912 --> 00:15:55,079
Thank you.

283
00:15:59,459 --> 00:16:01,293
Something's bothering you, it seems.

284
00:16:04,214 --> 00:16:06,215
That whole thing with Alan...

285
00:16:06,257 --> 00:16:08,550
Alan and I have been
having problems for years.

286
00:16:08,593 --> 00:16:10,219
That's why I had to let him go.

287
00:16:10,261 --> 00:16:15,099
Troy, I know you have
aspirations beyond this job.

288
00:16:15,141 --> 00:16:18,185
Well, no matter what you decide
to do in the future,

289
00:16:18,228 --> 00:16:20,604
you'll need life experience.
I can give you that.

290
00:16:20,647 --> 00:16:24,274
Some very big things
are about to happen for me.

291
00:16:24,317 --> 00:16:26,110
What kind of things?

292
00:16:26,152 --> 00:16:29,446
Well, Troy, why don't you
stick around a while,

293
00:16:29,489 --> 00:16:31,782
work with me?
Maybe you'll find out.

294
00:16:33,493 --> 00:16:35,119
Deal?

295
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:44,003
I dove in.

296
00:16:44,045 --> 00:16:46,880
My life became
all Buck Howard all the time.

297
00:16:46,923 --> 00:16:49,091
The auditoriums
we played in were old

298
00:16:49,134 --> 00:16:52,136
and usually half full
but Buck didn't seem to notice.

299
00:16:52,178 --> 00:16:54,805
The minute he came out on stage,
he was in his element.

300
00:16:54,848 --> 00:16:57,641
Buck walked the edge.
Everything he did,

301
00:16:57,684 --> 00:16:59,643
he made the impossible
seem possible.

302
00:16:59,686 --> 00:17:02,146
Isn't that wild?

303
00:17:02,188 --> 00:17:04,148
It's wild!

304
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:06,775
Buck did have his following,

305
00:17:06,818 --> 00:17:09,445
- and we went to them.
- I love this town!

306
00:17:09,487 --> 00:17:13,490
For some reason, the people
of Akron, Ohio went nuts for him.

307
00:17:13,533 --> 00:17:15,492
I saw parts of the country
I'd never seen before...

308
00:17:15,535 --> 00:17:18,662
- Welcome to Willamette, Oregon!
- I love this town!

309
00:17:18,705 --> 00:17:21,248
That I'd never heard of before...

310
00:17:21,291 --> 00:17:23,042
Welcome to Wausau, Wisconsin!

311
00:17:23,084 --> 00:17:24,793
I love this town!

312
00:17:24,836 --> 00:17:26,795
Buck did have his quirks.

313
00:17:26,838 --> 00:17:29,298
How much did you
tip the bellman?

314
00:17:29,340 --> 00:17:30,799
$2.00.

315
00:17:30,842 --> 00:17:32,676
That's it?

316
00:17:32,719 --> 00:17:34,636
You represent me, Troy.

317
00:17:34,679 --> 00:17:36,972
You're making me look cheap.

318
00:17:37,015 --> 00:17:39,266
Here you go. Thanks.

319
00:17:39,309 --> 00:17:41,435
Troy, can you come in here?

320
00:17:41,478 --> 00:17:44,605
Did you just give
the bellman $10.00?

321
00:17:44,647 --> 00:17:46,732
- Yes, why?
- It's far too much.

322
00:17:46,775 --> 00:17:49,359
$1.00 cash, American, per bag.

323
00:17:49,402 --> 00:17:50,527
I am not made of money.

324
00:17:53,865 --> 00:17:57,326
And sometimes
he went beyond quirky.

325
00:17:57,368 --> 00:17:59,828
They pick me up in a minivan.

326
00:17:59,871 --> 00:18:01,705
This show is already ruined!

327
00:18:01,748 --> 00:18:03,916
You are incompetent!

328
00:18:03,958 --> 00:18:07,002
Yeah, Buck could
be difficult, frustrating,

329
00:18:07,045 --> 00:18:10,255
and at times I had to wonder
why I put up with it all.

330
00:18:10,298 --> 00:18:12,508
Mr. Howard.

331
00:18:12,550 --> 00:18:14,802
I want to thank you
so much for having me.

332
00:18:14,844 --> 00:18:16,804
I just wanted to say,
though, I won't be doing

333
00:18:16,846 --> 00:18:18,514
the "You can call me RayJay" bit.

334
00:18:18,556 --> 00:18:19,932
I don't want to do that.

335
00:18:19,974 --> 00:18:22,726
And by the way,
is Mr. Takei here?

336
00:18:22,769 --> 00:18:26,814
Um, no, he's uh...
he won't be with us this year.

337
00:18:26,856 --> 00:18:28,690
My college roommate was managing

338
00:18:28,733 --> 00:18:30,192
a multimillion dollar hedge fund

339
00:18:30,235 --> 00:18:32,194
and here I was helping Buck Howard

340
00:18:32,237 --> 00:18:33,862
with his benefit
starring Gary Coleman

341
00:18:33,905 --> 00:18:35,697
and the guy from
the "Police Academy" movies.

342
00:18:37,367 --> 00:18:39,701
The strange thing
was that I didn't mind.

343
00:18:39,744 --> 00:18:41,870
- Hello, Buck Howard.
- It was kind of cool.

344
00:18:41,913 --> 00:18:44,248
Or sad, depending on how
you looked at it.

345
00:18:44,290 --> 00:18:46,041
You gotta tell me
how you do it.

346
00:18:46,084 --> 00:18:49,128
I keep getting older
and you look the same.

347
00:18:49,170 --> 00:18:51,338
- Clean living.
- Yeah, clean living,

348
00:18:51,381 --> 00:18:53,340
and keeping all your money
under a mattress, right?

349
00:18:53,383 --> 00:18:56,844
Anyhow, Buck, I want
to really thank you for calling me.

350
00:18:56,886 --> 00:19:01,223
You know,
nobody calls me anymore.

351
00:19:01,266 --> 00:19:03,892
Buck, we're ready to start.

352
00:19:05,103 --> 00:19:07,104
Have a great show, everyone.

353
00:19:12,819 --> 00:19:16,989
I would like to dedicate
this next song

354
00:19:17,031 --> 00:19:20,409
to a once very very
dear friend of mine,

355
00:19:22,036 --> 00:19:25,622
Sulu, from "the Star Trek,"

356
00:19:25,665 --> 00:19:27,624
Mr. George Takei.

357
00:19:27,667 --> 00:19:30,711
George,

358
00:19:32,297 --> 00:19:34,256
may the force be in you.

359
00:19:36,634 --> 00:19:40,470
What the world needs now...

360
00:19:40,513 --> 00:19:43,015
No matter
how corny Buck's show could be,

361
00:19:43,057 --> 00:19:45,475
and no matter how much
he yelled at me before it,

362
00:19:45,518 --> 00:19:47,477
I never missed
the money effect.

363
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:50,355
It was the one part of the show
that always amazed me.

364
00:19:50,398 --> 00:19:53,150
Ladies and gentlemen,
my money.

365
00:19:54,861 --> 00:19:58,280
Ladies and gentlemen,
my money.

366
00:19:58,323 --> 00:20:02,284
And without fail,
it always amazed the audience.

367
00:20:02,327 --> 00:20:04,578
True, it would be a pleasure
to retrieve it personally.

368
00:20:04,621 --> 00:20:09,124
As a gentlemen,
I fear I must refrain,

369
00:20:09,167 --> 00:20:12,294
for my money
is in your brassiere.

370
00:20:14,839 --> 00:20:19,468
Ladies and gentlemen,
there's the money!

371
00:20:19,510 --> 00:20:21,470
I hadn't found my place in the world.

372
00:20:21,512 --> 00:20:24,306
But this finale was Buck's place,

373
00:20:24,349 --> 00:20:26,308
and just getting to be a part of it

374
00:20:26,351 --> 00:20:29,937
made me feel like
I was on the right track.

375
00:20:29,979 --> 00:20:33,774
Troy, we have the last
of the Great Buck autograph seekers.

376
00:20:33,816 --> 00:20:38,737
A colored photograph.
To whom shall I address it?

377
00:20:38,780 --> 00:20:40,530
Dad, what are you doing here?

378
00:20:40,573 --> 00:20:43,867
I was gonna ask you
the same question.

379
00:20:45,370 --> 00:20:48,664
- Uh...
- Troy, this is your father?

380
00:20:48,706 --> 00:20:51,416
I didn't know
you had family in Leesburg.

381
00:20:51,459 --> 00:20:53,627
He doesn't.

382
00:20:53,670 --> 00:20:56,755
Sir, what a pleasure.

383
00:20:56,798 --> 00:20:58,715
I'm Buck Howard.

384
00:20:58,758 --> 00:21:01,760
But before
you congratulate me on the show

385
00:21:01,803 --> 00:21:03,512
I have to congratulate
you on something.

386
00:21:03,554 --> 00:21:06,473
I want you to know you have raised
a very fine young man

387
00:21:06,516 --> 00:21:08,558
who is doing
a wonderful job for me.

388
00:21:08,601 --> 00:21:10,727
Hmm. I thought
he was in law school,

389
00:21:10,770 --> 00:21:12,980
because that's what he told me.

390
00:21:13,022 --> 00:21:17,567
But I am thrilled to hear that
he's doing a wonderful job for you.

391
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:24,700
Uh-oh.

392
00:21:24,742 --> 00:21:28,829
You know, Mr. Gable,
I can imagine how you feel.

393
00:21:28,871 --> 00:21:31,581
My father didn't want me
to go into show business.

394
00:21:31,624 --> 00:21:33,375
He wanted me to be
an accountant.

395
00:21:33,418 --> 00:21:36,545
Obviously that wasn't my calling.

396
00:21:36,587 --> 00:21:39,214
Yeah, well, I'm not gonna touch that.

397
00:21:39,257 --> 00:21:43,677
But if carrying your bags
is Troy's calling, well then I just

398
00:21:43,720 --> 00:21:46,346
wasted a lot of money
on his education.

399
00:21:46,389 --> 00:21:49,224
- Dad.
- Troy, may I?

400
00:21:49,267 --> 00:21:51,560
You know, sir,
I have a theory about that.

401
00:21:51,602 --> 00:21:54,896
I call it my onwards
and upwards theory.

402
00:21:54,939 --> 00:21:57,983
Perhaps you noticed
in the musical portion of my...

403
00:21:58,026 --> 00:22:00,777
Listen, I'd like to
talk to my son alone.

404
00:22:03,781 --> 00:22:05,741
Very well.
I was merely trying to add

405
00:22:05,783 --> 00:22:09,411
a little perspectivo,
as the Latins say.

406
00:22:09,454 --> 00:22:11,121
I think you've done that.

407
00:22:12,290 --> 00:22:15,334
Very well. Good evening.

408
00:22:15,376 --> 00:22:20,130
Troy, you can bring that and toss
my salad when you get back to the hotel.

409
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:25,886
That's a hell of a guy.

410
00:22:25,928 --> 00:22:28,096
Dad, I'm sorry.

411
00:22:28,139 --> 00:22:31,308
I haven't heard from you
in over a month.

412
00:22:31,351 --> 00:22:34,811
I had to call your friends
like I was some kind of freaking cop.

413
00:22:34,854 --> 00:22:36,772
I know.

414
00:22:36,814 --> 00:22:39,775
I would have killed
to go to law school, Troy.

415
00:22:39,817 --> 00:22:41,568
I would have killed.

416
00:22:41,611 --> 00:22:43,904
I hated it.

417
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:47,115
- I wasn't happy. I...
- You think I danced out the front door

418
00:22:47,158 --> 00:22:49,534
every morning
in my adult life happy

419
00:22:49,577 --> 00:22:52,454
about where I was
gonna be spending my day?

420
00:22:52,497 --> 00:22:55,957
I don't know what
you're doing here.

421
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:58,794
I don't think you do either.

422
00:22:58,836 --> 00:23:02,047
But come on.
You're smarter than this.

423
00:23:02,090 --> 00:23:03,965
You are.

424
00:23:04,008 --> 00:23:06,510
You are smarter than this.

425
00:23:08,554 --> 00:23:10,347
I hope he enjoys his Cobb salad.

426
00:23:28,574 --> 00:23:31,993
I just don't think, uh...

427
00:23:32,036 --> 00:23:35,330
I don't think
I can do this anymore.

428
00:23:35,373 --> 00:23:38,375
I'm sorry.
I have to resign.

429
00:23:40,253 --> 00:23:41,753
I have to resign.

430
00:23:41,796 --> 00:23:43,839
Gil's not here yet?

431
00:23:45,007 --> 00:23:46,716
Uh, no, he's not.

432
00:23:46,759 --> 00:23:49,010
Buck, there's something
I need to discuss with you.

433
00:23:49,053 --> 00:23:51,847
Sorry I'm late. Traffic.

434
00:23:51,889 --> 00:23:55,016
Can we talk later?
We'll get back to this,

435
00:23:55,059 --> 00:23:57,769
but there is some business
I need to discuss.

436
00:23:57,812 --> 00:23:59,604
I've tried.

437
00:23:59,647 --> 00:24:02,274
I'm on the horn to the guys
at Leno, Letterman, every week.

438
00:24:02,316 --> 00:24:05,235
They want to have you on the show.
They're just booked tightly right now.

439
00:24:05,278 --> 00:24:08,196
Letterman I understand
because I don't have a history there.

440
00:24:08,239 --> 00:24:12,367
But this Jay Leno... I think
he's doing his show a great disservice

441
00:24:12,410 --> 00:24:15,537
by not having me. I practically built
"The Tonight Show."

442
00:24:15,580 --> 00:24:17,956
I know we need to get you
some attention right now.

443
00:24:17,999 --> 00:24:19,958
I speak to the bookers in Vegas.

444
00:24:20,001 --> 00:24:21,418
I tell them you're better now
than you've ever been.

445
00:24:21,461 --> 00:24:23,879
They tell me
they just need to see it.

446
00:24:23,921 --> 00:24:26,423
If they need to see something,

447
00:24:26,466 --> 00:24:28,717
I've got something
I can show them.

448
00:24:32,513 --> 00:24:36,725
For the past three years
I have been rehearsing in secret

449
00:24:36,767 --> 00:24:39,561
a new effect. I can't even tell
either of you what it is.

450
00:24:39,604 --> 00:24:42,856
It's not that I don't trust you,
but I cannot afford

451
00:24:42,899 --> 00:24:45,233
that the tabloids
get a hold of this now.

452
00:24:45,276 --> 00:24:49,613
Let me just say it is enormous.

453
00:24:49,655 --> 00:24:53,366
And I think Cincinnati is
the perfect place to unveil it.

454
00:24:53,409 --> 00:24:56,578
They have always
loved me in Ohio.

455
00:24:56,621 --> 00:25:00,624
Not so much Ohio,
but Akron.

456
00:25:00,666 --> 00:25:03,919
It's close to Cincinnat...
it's the same state.

457
00:25:03,961 --> 00:25:08,423
I need you to call Steve Keating
in New York at the top P.R. firm.

458
00:25:08,466 --> 00:25:11,426
I want local press
and national press.

459
00:25:11,469 --> 00:25:15,096
I can feel this.
It's gonna be huge.

460
00:25:15,139 --> 00:25:17,140
Cincinnati.

461
00:25:25,942 --> 00:25:27,859
Welcome to Cincinnati!

462
00:25:27,902 --> 00:25:28,985
I love this town!

463
00:25:29,028 --> 00:25:30,862
- I'm Doreen.
- How do you do?

464
00:25:30,905 --> 00:25:32,322
I'm Buck Howard.

465
00:25:32,365 --> 00:25:34,407
This is my brother Kenny.

466
00:25:34,450 --> 00:25:36,868
- Hello, Kenny. How are you?
- Good.

467
00:25:36,911 --> 00:25:39,120
On behalf of both of us,

468
00:25:39,163 --> 00:25:42,499
and the Cincinnati chapter
of the Red Hat Society,

469
00:25:42,542 --> 00:25:47,546
I'd like to present you
with this pin.

470
00:25:49,799 --> 00:25:51,299
Well, my goodness.

471
00:25:51,342 --> 00:25:53,468
Isn't that beautiful?
Ow!

472
00:25:53,511 --> 00:25:56,012
- Oh!
- Agh! Mmm!

473
00:25:56,055 --> 00:25:58,139
You may have
drawn blood there.

474
00:25:58,182 --> 00:25:59,808
- I'm so sorry.
- It's all right.

475
00:25:59,850 --> 00:26:01,851
It's a beautiful pin
from a beautiful woman

476
00:26:01,894 --> 00:26:03,770
and I will wear it
while I'm here.

477
00:26:03,813 --> 00:26:06,189
The entire time I'm here,
I'll wear it for good luck.

478
00:26:06,232 --> 00:26:09,025
Boy, I love to come
to these venues before the show,

479
00:26:09,068 --> 00:26:12,153
but I'm afraid I'm gonna have to
get back to the hotel

480
00:26:12,196 --> 00:26:14,823
because my press relations attache

481
00:26:14,865 --> 00:26:18,660
has flown in for a rendezvous
from the borough of Manhattan.

482
00:26:18,703 --> 00:26:20,829
That's no problem at all.
We're your hosts.

483
00:26:20,871 --> 00:26:24,833
We'll be taking you anywhere you need
to go the whole time you're here.

484
00:26:24,875 --> 00:26:26,835
That's how we do it
in Cincinnati.

485
00:26:26,877 --> 00:26:30,130
I'm gonna drive you.
We got a limo and everything.

486
00:26:34,093 --> 00:26:38,638
I saw you, 1989,
Bowling Green University.

487
00:26:38,681 --> 00:26:41,182
You were awesome!
Do you remember that?

488
00:26:41,225 --> 00:26:45,312
Honestly, I do
vaguely remember that.

489
00:26:45,354 --> 00:26:47,939
But of course that's
nearly 20 years ago,

490
00:26:47,982 --> 00:26:50,525
and I do 400 or so shows a year.

491
00:26:50,568 --> 00:26:53,028
You do 400 shows a year?

492
00:26:55,072 --> 00:26:57,907
Yeah, uh, I'm doing
the calculations in my head...

493
00:26:57,950 --> 00:26:59,909
You might want
to face that way.

494
00:26:59,952 --> 00:27:03,371
And I don't even see how 300 dates
is physically possible. I mean...

495
00:27:05,416 --> 00:27:07,792
that's pretty much
a show every night, you know?

496
00:27:07,835 --> 00:27:10,003
I mean, where do you perform
on Monday and Tuesday nights

497
00:27:10,046 --> 00:27:12,213
and how does that
allow for travel time?

498
00:27:12,256 --> 00:27:16,968
Troy, he has to be checked in
by now. It's Steve Keating. K-e-a.

499
00:27:17,011 --> 00:27:20,555
